FX ORDER WATCH

Our new FX Order Watch service keeps a constant check on the currency markets. You can set your own preferred exchange rate between two currencies—for example US Dollars and Euro.
Through Citibank Online, you can select the rate at which you want to trade, and the term over which you want the exchange to happen.
Then place different orders (Simple Buy/Sell Order or One-Cancels-Other Order), in your desired currency:

(EUR)
(USD)
(GBP)
(AUD)
(JPY)
(CAD)
(NZD)
(CHF)
(UAE)


This is a non-advised product. Citibank, N.A. UAE does not offer any recommendation for specific transaction with currency pairs, tenures and exchange rates. Detailed FX Order Watch Terms and Conditions are available on www.citibank.ae and also on the FX Order Watch page in Citibank Online.



INTERNATIONAL PERSONAL BANK

Managing your wealth offshore across different markets allows you to diversify risk, access new investment opportunities and hold accounts in different currencies. It gives you freedom to live and work where you want, while accessing a wide range of sophisticated investment products, many of which may not be available where you currently live.
Your investment strategy will be handled through Booking Centers in London, Jersey or Singapore. Whichever one you choose, you can be sure that your assets are being managed though one of the world's most stable and secure financial centers.

London is widely considered the world's number one financial market and attracts some of the best talent in the world
Jersey is well established as a leading offshore financial center and has long been a key base for offshore banking and private wealth management
Singapore has a stable political environment, robust banking infrastructure and regulations, and global outlook

These booking centers may also offer you a time-zone advantage over your country of residence and support in multiple languages.
Investments in London, Jersey and Singapore are tightly regulated by the Financial Conduct Authority, Jersey Financial Services Commission and the Monetary Authority of Singapore, respectively.





